name: Gleb Podkolzin
title: Senior Staff Engineer
headline: Sr. Staff Engineer at Uber
description:
I like empowering customers to make informed, data-driven business-critical decisions through good and reliable tools. I specialize in engineering, design, and other kinds of problem solving on the web, and sometimes on mobile.

I have expertise in Javascript, React (hooks and contexts and all that v16+ stuff), GraphQL w/ Apollo, Redux, CSS in JS, some Webpack, raw HTML/CSS where needed, Jest with Enzyme with testing, node.js (Express, Koa). Also like working with Redis caches and finding other ways of enhancing the customer experience. Data stores - I've worked with MySQL, Cassandra, ELK across various projects.

Outside of JS, I have experience in Python, C++, Java, Objective-C with graphics frameworks like GLKit. Limited understanding of OpenGL ES. Currently learning Swift + Metal.

Heavy Photoshop user, can also construct mockups in Figma (past: Sketch, Illustrator).

Hobbies: self-driving cars, music, drawing, and some 3d graphics/VFX basics.

name: Kay Ashaolu
title: Continuing Lecturer
headline: I help junior software engineers learn how to design systems end to end in the first year of their career
description: Passionate about accelerating early-career growth, I blend my experience as a software engineer, manager, and university lecturer in web architecture to empower junior engineers. I firmly believe that with the right guidance, they can contribute to designing complex systems typically considered beyond their expertise. Leveraging my industry and academic experience, I focus on teaching tried-and-true front-end and back-end components and how they can be connected to build complex systems. My mission is to bridge the knowledge gap by providing resources that help junior engineers master system design.

Responsible for keeping Lyft developers productive whether they are iterating on unit tests in their IDE or using the app to debug issues.","company_logo":"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4E0BAQG5JWwh4GET8A/company-logo_400_400/B4EZdbVQ6oHcAg-/0/1749583990773/lyft_logo?e=1756944000&v=beta&t=y42kfO0qkk_306rTO_cjrbqXvQzERBlWKYGgxnGaBl4","company_name":"Lyft"},{"title":"Senior Staff Software Engineer","end_date":"2018-02-01T00:00:00","location":"San Francisco Bay Area","start_date":"2012-06-01T00:00:00","description":"Team lead of large scale initiative to migrate from an aurora/mesos datacenter to kubernetes in AWS in order to meet growing needs of business while containing cost. 

Built, maintained, and sunset over the course of 5 years several distributed data stores aimed at supporting workloads not suited for mongodb. These “model services” are a system to export mongo’s replication logs to kafka and aggregate the updates in a stateful service to cache joins in redis. 

Built a read-only key-value store to deliver offline data to our online services called hfile service. Developed open-source replacement written in go called quiver. Rewriting in go lowered per process overhead enough to enable a single process per hfile. Wrote orchestration tool to automatically verify and deploy new data from our HDFS cluster. 

Built delta-service to combine offline data with mongodb. Quiver serves the majority of the data cheaply while mongodb stores write on a short TTL. Engineers use a reimplementation of our ORM rogue. 

Team lead on an experimental key-value store called “Kyiv” to replace our model services. Kyiv is a scala service that stored data in rocksdb. It also uses Kafka as a distributed write log, and aurora/mesos to provide scheduling. Gobblin was used to create rollups from kafka to allow kyiv instances to bootstrap. 
Rewrote image resizer service to lower machine costs. After 5 years of running in production, migrated to imgix to reduce overall cost and remove technical debt. 

Lead initiatives to raise standards around code review, launches, infrastructure changes, and post-mortems. Run a weekly meeting to facilitate cross-team discussion of large code or architectural changes. Member of our on-call rotation. Responsible for responding to alerts and resolving incidents. 

Provide direct mentorship to junior team members. Hold office hours to provide guidance on infrastructure to support new products.

headline: Senior Software Engineer at Airbnb
description:
Solid background in the fundamentals of software development, and have a deep understanding of best practices in website and application development, including cross-browser compatibility, building rich browser based user experience and cross-platform application.

Proficient in Java to develop and build cutting-edge production software and experienced in building distributed systems/web services. 

Capable of working under immense pressure and strict deadlines.  Fast learner that welcome all kinds of challenges.

Programming: Java, HTML/CSS, JavaScript /AJAX, PHP, JSP/Servlet, YUI, SQL, MVC, UML, XML, Perl
Tools: Eclipse, VIM, JUnit, Selenium, Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSql, Neo4j, Tomcat, Dreamweaver, Firebug
Development: Object-Oriented Design (OOD), System Design, Agile Development, Quality Assurance, Blockchain

I enjoy explaining complex technical systems in non technical terms, getting up to speed quickly with new languages and systems, and digging deep to find that elusive bug. 

I've been at Stripe since 2015 where I spent most of my time helping our largest customers and strategic partners build their integrations.  These days I'm excited to use that experience as a developer advocate, helping developers get started on Stripe. 

I'm also a jazz and swing musician, you can find out more about my music at http://www.dawnlambeth.com

description:
Engineering Manager for the Pinterest Homefeed Candidate Generation team.  Our mission is to find the most personalized, relevant pins for your Pinterest Homefeed.  We do this all on-demand and in realtime, fetching from a corpus of billions of pins, while using different recommendation algorithms.

Previously, I was the backend lead for Watch Tab and worked on different areas related to recommendations on Homefeed at Pinterest, covering the entire stack from candidate generation to serving to new product features.  I've also worked on local search and autocomplete for maps at Apple.  I have experience in recommendations, machine learning, large scale data processing, and distributed systems.

name: Alex Zylman
title: Senior Staff Engineer
headline: Senior Staff Engineer at Uber
description:
I'm an experienced technical leader. I focus on designing and building scalable, fault-tolerant systems that anticipate the needs of the business.

Currently I'm reporting to the head of commerce, leading efforts across 15+ teams in 5+ countries to unify disparate systems into a cohesive "Commerce Platform" to serve complex business requirements across Uber's growing number of product lines.

Previously, I managed 1/3rd of Clever's engineering team, focusing primarily on infrastructure where I built out the Docker-based deployment and observability tooling on AWS. 

Even more previously, I built out Clever's data pipeline and task queue system that ingested roster data, profiled and improved latency in critical services, developed an iOS app that jump-started our growth, and continually kept in mind the needs of our customers.

Specialties: Building things

name: Tomo Otsuka
title: Senior Software Engineer
headline: Senior Software Engineer at Airbnb
description:
I am a passionate full-stack engineer that thrives on tackling challenging problems with collaborative teams. I enjoy writing and fostering coding philosophies and patterns that enhances testability, readability, productivity, maintainability, and scalability of the codebase.

During the last 12 years I've built backends from the ground up (application, platform, database, and API design), invested in infrastructure (AWS, deploy, monitoring tools), and utilized several different front-end stacks (jQuery, Backbone, React, and Android).

name: Han Xu
title: Software Engineer
headline: Palantir Engineering
description:
Financial analyst turned full stack developer and data analytics expert.  At Stripe, I led Professional Services in APAC, growing that team from four to over twenty people across the region. I have led teams on many projects deploying and integrating data analytics platforms and payments systems into complicated enterprise stacks.  I like to be hands on and try to get a deep understanding of the problem space and technical solutions whenever possible.

Primary languages are Python (e.g. Spark, Django, Scikit) and JavaScript (e.g. Angular, D3), with some experience in Ruby (Rails) and R.  Cloud deployment and DevOps experience is primarily with Amazon AWS and Google Compute Engine using Ansible.  I've dabbled in Haskell, Node, and Android / Java.

My previous experience in the financial industry includes roles as on a multi-asset portfolio management team, conducting research and risk management, and in corporate fundamental analysis.

name: Matthew Hiller
title: Staff Software Engineer
headline: Staff Software Engineer at Tock
location: New York, New York, United States
description:
I'm a builder of software and software systems that stay fairly close to what the user sees. And I'm nice about most things, but sad to say most recruiting reachouts just don't come correct for me. More below.

--

Please do not email me with a cold reachout if:

* Your message is not tailored to me
* The opportunity is at a beak-of-the-vampire-squid finance operation of some sort
* The same as above, but doubled, if it has something to do with some sort of crypto/NFT/blockchain scam-flavor of the week
* You have previously emailed me and I did not reply, to "bump it up to the top of my inbox"
^ honestly, I probably auto-blocked you after the first email anyway. I'm prone to doing that
* The job is fully remote/distributed. I'm an in-offices person.

Think very hard before emailing a cold reachout if:

* The "open to" settings on my profile do not show that I am considering moving to another job. I will use this feature appropriately, and I will take the usual privacy measures so as not to broadcast this to insiders at my current company.

description:
At Netflix, my role as a Staff Software Engineer finds me at the forefront of developing Mantis, our stream processing engine for operational needs, as well as Flink, a stream processing engine tailored for analytical use-cases. 

Previously, at Uber, I led the creation of SubmitQueue and uCI, systems that were created to provide an always green master for large monorepos.

Some of the projects I have been involved with:

Submit Queue:
100s of engineers committing changes concurrently to a repository leads to frequent master breakages. At Uber, Submit Queue handles 100s of commits/hr submitted by ~1000 of engineers every day.

Individual contributions made:
-- Came up the idea of speculatively executing builds that are mostly likely to succeed to scale the system to 100s of commits/hr.
-- Designed and implemented a conflict analyzer to detect if two changes are likely to conflict or not using the build system.
-- Built Machine Learning models that continuously learn & estimate the likelihood of changes to pass builds.
-- Architected the system to handle 100s of repositories, failover-active in all of Uber's regions.
-- Published a research paper at Eurosys'19 introducing SubmitQueue and detailing its core components.

uCI - a reliable task execution/orchestration system for stateful workloads:
Laid the foundation for a world class CI Infrastructure at Uber by replacing Jenkins with a scalable task execution system that leverages mesos for cluster management.

name: Andrew Archer
title: Senior Software Engineer
headline: Senior Software Engineer at Airbnb
description:
I love to see people use the things we build.

Whether that's Slack's "Custom Status" feature or the external account linking flow at Wealthfront -- I've felt a profound sense of accomplishment when people engage with things I've created.

Before working as a Frontend Engineer at Slack and Wealthfront, I spent eight years at Google as at TPM and in Operations working closely with product and engineering teams.

In 2014, I took a sabbatical from Google to complete Dev Bootcamp and convert my hobbyist's interest in software development into my vocation. I enjoyed researching new technologies, writing clean code, pairing with peers, and performing behavior- and test-driven development.

My mission now is to continue learning, code every day with others, and build software that people love.

name: Jeff Mohan
title: Senior Engineer
headline: Senior Software Engineer
description:
Software engineer trying to help the world run a little smoother. 

Previously, I co-founded Chewse to make workplaces better and helped bring it to success — $12M in annual sales, 100+ employees, $15M raised. I programmed the site that got us our first funding, I built an engineering and design team of 10 amazing people, and I ran operations and logistics for almost a year. 

Engineering is my passion. I love the act of creation, of bringing something into the world and changing people's lives so directly. So now I'm back to building the web out of incredible open-source technologies like Ruby, Rails, Python, Django, React, Angular, VueJS, and more.

name: Takashi Okamoto
title: Software Engineer
headline: Software Engineer at Palantir
description:
Takashi Okamoto's illustrations have appeared in magazines and newspapers including: The New York Times, The Walrus, The National Post and Shift Magazine. As a graphic designer, he has worked with studios including 2x4, Stiletto, Village and artists Ben Rubin and Natalie Jeremijenko. His technology based art has been exhibited in Canada, Mexico and Spain.

Currently he is a web engineer at Palantir in Palo Alto, CA. He received his Honours Bachelor of Science in Astrophysics from the University of Toronto, a Master of Fine Arts in graphic design from Yale University and a Master of Science from the MIT Media Lab.

name: Michael Harris
title: Tech Lead
headline: Senior Tech Leader | Microservices Architect | High-Performance Systems Builder
description: Technology is my passion and life is just as important. I focus on work-life balance and try to find the best combination between the two. Outside of work, I like to read, travel, spend time with my family and friends, draw energy from life and maintain a positive and optimistic mindset. I later turned these utilities into a shared library which is used across Block for our different web SDKs.

* Lead the Metrics Workstream, a set of 3 projects, consisting of 3 engineers and a data scientist, to improve metrics collection and introduce an A/B testing framework for the Web Payments SDK. I wrote the engineering design doc and implemented a custom A/B test framework for the Web Payments SDK, leading the first two A/B tests to reduce address verification rejections for credit card payments.

• Managed a cross functional team that completely redesigned the mechanical manufacturing process by creating a system controlled assembly application. The system went through multiple refinements, based on post implementation analysis of production and defect data. Outcomes included increased throughput, reducing per unit assembly times up to 60%, leading to an average labor savings of 300 worker-hours per month. Furthermore, the process curtailed internally reported defects from an initial 15.4 DPMO to a post implementation rate of 1.6 DPMO. 

• Managed a team of Industrial Engineers, across multiple sites, to implement system wide solutions to the stocking and kitting processes. By developing and implementing a standardized material stocking, consolidation, and tracking processes, we were able to reduce kitting and stocking related labor costs by 28 worker hours/day.

• Designed a process specific analysis program, with SQL/VBA, to identify root causes of operational performance gaps and production line shutdowns. Using that data, I programmed and implemented an electronic scheduler to ensure kit production kept proper pace with the assembly lines’ component demands. The average cycle time for kits was reduced by over 10 days per kit, 25% of their aging, while production downtime was reduced by over 10 worker hours/ day.

description:
At Uber, our team has achieved remarkable milestones, including the development of large-scale MERN stack applications and leading server-side infrastructure, which significantly elevated client satisfaction and operational efficiency. With expertise in cloud computing and software development, I've contributed to deploying CI/CD pipelines that cut deployment times by 40% and increased frequency by half. 

My focus is on pioneering solutions that harness the power of cloud computing, particularly within the AWS ecosystem, to foster robust and scalable web architectures. Collaborating closely with cross-functional teams, we have cultivated a culture of continuous improvement, ensuring high-quality software and a stellar user experience for our diverse client base.

name: Sumedh Sakdeo
title: Senior Staff Software Engineer, Data Infra
headline: Creator openhousedb.org, ex-Head of Data Lyft Self Driving Division
description: Distributed System, Data Infrastructure, Data Analytics, Data Engineering, Data Visualization, Stream & Batch Processing, File System
experience:
[{"title":"Senior Staff Software Engineer, Data Infra","end_date":"1970-01-01T00:00:00","location":"Sunnyvale, California, United States","start_date":"2021-09-01T00:00:00","description":"Created OpenHouse at LinkedIn.

Product and Technical Lead for OpenHouse: A New Open Data Lakehouse Architecture for the Cloud. 

https://engineering.linkedin.com/blog/2023/taking-charge-of-tables--introducing-openhouse-for-big-data-mana
https://www.linkedin.com/blog/engineering/open-source/open-sourcing-openhouse

In the world of Big Data Management, there's always a tussle between control and flexibility! Cloud data warehouse solutions maintain tight control over the systems, which allows data infrastructure teams to ensure proper governance, data integrity, security, and performance. However, these systems often suffer from a lack of flexibility and scale. That's where open source data lake(house) systems come into play. 

At LinkedIn, we self-manage an open source data lakehouse deployment, and we have faced challenges in providing a managed experience for our end-users. Loss of managed experience often means our end-users have to deal with low-level infra concerns, diluting their core product focus. Moreover, our data infra teams are left with little control on the system we operate, making it harder for us to regulate proper governance and optimization.

Control that liberates is a paradoxical idea, where a well implemented control mechanism can actually empower data infra teams to “regain control” so that they can govern better, and liberate end-users from low level infra concerns by providing them a fully managed offering.

OpenHouse is materialization of this idea!","company_logo":"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/C560BAQHaVYd13rRz3A/company-logo_400_400/company-logo_400_400/0/1638831590218/linkedin_logo?e=1756339200&v=beta&t=Wa8H5FNWW0EXbItBEV3V6-triqUVxocouEv0F0clV5Q","company_name":"LinkedIn"},{"title":"Mentor","end_date":"2022-08-01T00:00:00","location":"","start_date":"2021-07-01T00:00:00","description":"Volunteering as a Plato Mentor

Data Platform & Products (Based in Palo Alto, USA and London, UK)

We worked on solving problems in large scale distributed system (kafka, data warehouse, data lakes) and creating clean, easy to use web APIs (http/grpc).

Data Visualization
Our team also builds cutting edge data visualization tools for interactive slicing and dicing of data, which can take you from an idea to a chart within 1min, without having to write a single line of SQL code. Data Engineering

I value transparency and honesty, and I strive to create a culture of collaboration and feedback.

name: Anand Doshi
title: Lead Design Technologist
headline: Design Technologist at Square
description:
Hello! 

I am Anand, a product designer with extensive software engineering experience. I would describe myself as a generalist: I am curious about everything, creative, and rigorous. I enjoy working with others, and appreciate the feeling of being considered dependable.

For 5 years, I worked as a CTO / Full-stack Engineer at a startup in Mumbai, where I wore many hats, and built an open-source business application as part of a small team. I went to grad school to study UX Design, and worked on a wide variety of projects involving UX research, digital and tangible interactions, and graphic design.

At the moment, I live in Berkeley and work at Square / Block Inc. as a Sr. Design Technologist.

name: Freeland Abbott
title: Technical Lead
headline: Tech Lead & Software Engineer at Square
description:
Please don't talk to me about relocation.  I live in Boulder, CO; my wife's job is here, and I'm not about to mess her up for your once-in-a-lifetime opportunity in San Francisco or New York or wherever.  For that matter, I'm pretty happy as I am... but I'm willing to talk about other options near Boulder.  Not so much about things elsewhere.

That out of the way, I'm a senior software engineer, full-stack including JavaScript and Android.  I've held management and leadership jobs, and might interested in returning to that with a local-office environment (which I haven't had in a while, which is why I didn't try to keep that role).  I code in Kotlin, Java, Go, C/C++, Python, Javascript, and other languages.  I'm familiar with many of Google's cloud products, and at least aware of the analogous AWS offerings.  I also know Android, and I'm open to learning iOS but haven't yet had to.

Outside of work, I juggle, I do woodworking (minor cabinetry and home improvement, mostly), and these days I've swapped out playing flute and ultimate for keeping track of teen children and too dang many pets.

Data group mission was to capture, organize, transform, and serve all the self-driving data. Self-driving program generated ~100TB of data per day, and we provided everything needed to make it accessible and useful to diverse set of data consumers, ranging from ML engineers to business analysts. This organization owned Data Logging, Core Data Stores, Data Lake, Data Engineering, Streaming and Batch Frameworks, and ML Platform. Key technologies: BigQuery, ElasticSearch, DynamoDB, Kafka, Sagemaker, and Flyte. 

Infrastructure team was responsible for all the Level 5 cloud footprint. We provided geographically distributed, multi-cloud, and hybrid cloud compute and storage deployment at scale. Our cloud budget was in tens of millions dollars annually - managing and optimizing costs was a big part of the team charter. We were also responsible for core developer experience of all Level 5 software engineers with particular focus on build and observability. Key technologies: AWS, GCP, Kubernetes, Terraform, Wavefront, and Bazel. 

Open Platform was a full stack (backend, web, mobile) consumer facing team responsible for the user experience of Lyft riders as they interacted with self-driving cars in real world (both in the Lyft app and while riding in a self-driving car). Autonomous marketplace, where partners like Waymo or Motional offered their self-driving rides to Lyft customers, was also part of Open Platform responsibility.

[{"title":"VP of Engineering / Sr. Director / Director (Chief Engineer)","end_date":"2023-12-01T00:00:00","location":"Seattle","start_date":"2017-01-01T00:00:00","description":"As Snap grew from pre-IPO startup to 750MM MAU / $4.6B revenue, I had 3 core responsibilities.

As chief software architect, I reported to the COO / SVP of Eng (Jerry Hunter) and owned tech direction for a growing scope of 450 engineers at first to a peak of 2350. Snapchat is a complex “12 mobile apps in 1”, with thousands of back-end servers running across AWS, GCP and on-prem. Each feature wants all the resources of a phone to create the most compelling experience. This means orchestrating concurrent and battery efficient use of network, CPU, GPU, APU, video codecs and camera – much like an OS. Components need clean isolation to avoid corruption or hogging by background features while maximizing the customer’s experience for whatever they are engaging at the moment.

API design was not enough to achieve this, so I also led technical ops. The hardest aspect was building our Customer Experience Program (CEPP) that ensured features and platform components achieved performance, battery and metrics accuracy goals. This scaled from app startup latency and messaging reliability to 50 areas and 500 customer-focused “end to end” metrics. I built cross-functional collaborations across eng, design, monetization and finance in several ops programs including CEPP, where we reported and reviewed metrics in weekly leadership forums. I used these to ensure API and service shortfalls were being continuously identified and renovated to meet the demands of new features, growing scale and cost.

Last, I owned key aspects of Eng culture: designing and (co-)authoring the Eng ladder system, roles \ leveling \ hiring guidelines, OKR framework, and perf \ calibration \ promo process. I built the Eng promo and hiring budget analysis with HR, to ensure a healthy balance of level distributions. location: New York, New York, United States
experience:
[{"title":"Senior Prinicipal Engineer","end_date":"2019-06-01T00:00:00","location":"Greater New York City Area","start_date":"2019-03-01T00:00:00","description":"In 2017-2018, shifting gears once again, I led work on expanding our service oriented approach and culture from infra teams, to all our application and product backend teams. This project didn't involve building any new systems. Primary challenge was coordinating across almost half of our whole engineering organization, getting everyone excited on this new direction and getting everyone to accept and agree to the same shared standards and guidelines. 

In 2018-2019, switched back to working more as an IC once again. As my last large project at Dropbox, I worked on rebuilding and fully rewriting our metrics collection and querying systems. As part of this project, I also helped build out our observability/monitoring team in NYC. Project turned out quite well overall, some highlights:
- New system finally allowed us to collect and query all sorts of metrics, including percentile breakdowns even for our largest scale systems. 
- New system was ~2x cheaper compared to what it replaced (and orders of magnitude cheaper compared to external paid offerings), while at the same time providing more features, more granularity, and much better latencies from collecting a metric to seeing it show up on graphs.","company_logo":"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/C560BAQHjnNsmL5L2NA/company-logo_400_400/company-logo_400_400/0/1654114493492/dropbox_logo?e=1756944000&v=beta&t=evN6WnOoNoe_tx-XRy05THGdmBJgNW-9m2AUuyk-mJo","company_name":"Dropbox"},{"title":"Principal Engineer","end_date":"2019-03-01T00:00:00","location":"","start_date":"2014-11-01T00:00:00","description":"In ~2014 we built out and grew our infrastructure to run in multiple regions (we called it "multi homing"), and we also set on a path to have more consistent "hybrid infrastructure" setup where systems in our own data-centers and systems in AWS would become more consistent and easier to manage together. I was heavily involved in a lot of the projects to facilitate this:
- Worked on multi homing our internal machine database and service discovery systems. As part of this project, also worked with others to standardize our infrastructure topology and created shared understandable standard between our Software, Network and Datacenters teams. 
- Did a lot of the initial designs of how to multi home all our other services, including Databases/Edgestore

Sometime in 2015, I moved to NYC. 
- Helped build our first infrastructure team in NYC. By the time I left in 2019, infra presence in NYC had grown to ~4-5 core teams and a lot of great engineers.
- Worked on various projects during this time, mostly to grow the team in NYC. As port of these projects built out a new type of testing framework that allowed us to write and run integration tests in controlled repeatable environments. While we ended up replacing the system few years later, all of its core ideas remained intact and we drastically improved integration testing abilities for our infra services. 

In 2016-2017, I spent a lot of time on performance. As the culmination of all the perf work, I worked on building new distributed in-memory hash table system that replaced all our Memcache deployments. 
- This new system was fully written in GO, and had 99 percentile latencies in single digit milliseconds.
- Rewriting this system allowed us to finally fix a lot hacky workarounds for our consistency protocols, and in addition to improving correctness guarantees, it opened up new paths for our multi homing related projects in databases.","company_logo":"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/C560BAQHjnNsmL5L2NA/company-logo_400_400/company-logo_400_400/0/1654114493492/dropbox_logo?e=1756944000&v=beta&t=evN6WnOoNoe_tx-XRy05THGdmBJgNW-9m2AUuyk-mJo","company_name":"Dropbox"},{"title":"Software Engineer","end_date":"2014-11-01T00:00:00","location":"San Francisco Bay Area","start_date":"2011-06-01T00:00:00","description":"Joined DBX as 4th (or 5th?) engineer on infrastructure team.
- Initially spent time working on our EC2/AWS infrastructure parts. But as all other members of the team, I was also heavily involved in our very high paced operations and fire fighting during our exponential growth phase.
- Built out our first Hadoop/HDFS/HBase setup and built our internal logging systems and libraries. Also rebuilt our server application exception and error reporting system, which remained in use (for better or worse, but mostly worse) at least until 2019.

Sometime in 2012-2013 switched to working on our databases. Built Edgestore, a distributed database, that over the years became defacto metadata storage for all of DBX, storing all metadata except for file journaling information in it. As part of this project, I also helped bring many changes to all of infrastructure:
- With few others, pioneered use of GoLang at DBX, and built a lot of the internal core libraries in it.
- Started moving our infrastructure towards service oriented architecture. As part of that effort, built first versions of our packaging and deployment systems and also our service discovery system that was integrated into our RPC framework.

Overall these projects turned out quite well: Edgestore grew as the main metadata storage system at DBX, GO became our main language for building infra services, and we successfully moved into service oriented setup for all our infrastructure.","company_logo":"https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/C560BAQHjnNsmL5L2NA/company-logo_400_400/company-logo_400_400/0/1654114493492/dropbox_logo?e=1756944000&v=beta&t=evN6WnOoNoe_tx-XRy05THGdmBJgNW-9m2AUuyk-mJo","company_name":"Dropbox"},{"title":"Software Engineer - Intern","end_date":"2010-08-01T00:00:00","location":"","start_date":"2010-06-01T00:00:00","description":"Worked with Google Front End server team as a Software Engineer Intern. Worked on the server side implementation of the SPDY protocol. SPDY is an experimental protocol for the web, its goal is to reduce the load time of web pages and to make the Internet faster. My main project involved working on the implementation of flow control for SPDY. During my internship I had to closely work with the Chrome team since they were developing the client side of the flow control. description: Online marketing mode and offline marketing mode is opposed to each other but interdependent. On the one hand, the emergence of e-commerce platforms has impacted the development of the real economy, and nowadays, many consumers tend to shop online conveniently and cheaply, which leads to the declining sales of offline stores and the shrinking of the real economy to a certain extent; on the other hand, the real economy is an important foundation of a country's economy, and if the real economy cannot develop healthily, the virtual economy will also be affected to a greater extent. At the same time, the recovery and development of the real economy will certainly also seize the market and sales of the online platform, affecting the development of e-commerce platform. The contradiction between online marketing mode and offline marketing mode determines that it is difficult for the real economy and the virtual economy to survive and develop independently, and only by combining with each other can we achieve a win-win situation.

name: Sophia C.
headline: Early Uber engineer and scrappy technologist
description:
I thrive in fast paced, idiosyncratic, get stuff done environments.

As one of the first 20 engineers at Uber, I loved the repeated experiences of going from 0 to 1 and then scaling through the hyper growth phases; I was a founding engineer for the mapping and routing team, managed a rapidly growing team going from 3 to 20+ in 2 years, and helped get the Uber Freight team off the ground as a founding engineer.

After Uber, I traveled extensively, built an apple picking robot from scratch, and created a robust machine learning based stock trading system that traded $221mm worth of securities.

If you’ve made it this far and want to talk, a book recommendation makes it more likely for me to open a message.

name: Peter Leeds
title: Principle Software Engineer
headline: Software Engineer at Meta
description:
I believe that computer programming can change the world for the better.  With every passing day people become more and more overwhelmed by choices in their lives and in the marketplace.  Algorithms have the potential to help people deal with and overcome decision fatigue.  This is what I do.  I write code to make decisions for people.  

People don't need to make decisions anymore.  Most people don't want to.  I firmly believe that most people can't really be trusted to make decisions for themselves.  The companies that I partner with are better equipped to make informed purchasing and life decisions than their customers and users.  I help them do this.  It is a profound responsibility to design human choice, but I am willing to pick up this mantle and ride forth  into the brave new world where we plan the future  for all mankind.

name: Caitlin Colgrove
title: Co-Founder and CTO
headline: Co-Founder and CTO at Hex
description:
What I love most about being a software engineer is building products that combine the best parts of technological solutions with human expertise to solve problems in the real world. I've built mobile search interfaces for police officers, providing instant access to life-saving information; document analysis and triage applications for lawyers, improving the accuracy and efficiency of the e-discovery process by orders of magnitude; and collaborative, high-scale data analysis tools for the engineers who diagnose and fix critical issues with in-service aircraft.

Though I've spent most of my development time building modern web interfaces, I've also learned that delivering an excellent product requires attention across the entire stack, from the product vision and user experience down to the nuts and bolts of the backend services. I've never been afraid to move up and down the stack to address whatever the most pressing technical challenge is at the time.

Technology is important, but all software teams are also made up of people, which is why I invest a lot of my time in areas like hiring and people growth. I discovered a love of teaching while in college and have continued that pursuit in industry, first through mentorship and later as a people manager for the engineering team I lead. As manager, I've grown people into senior engineers and leads of their own teams – it's been one of the most rewarding aspects of my job.
